# What Is JSON-LD (and Why You Want It)

JSON-LD = **structured data for search engines**.

It‚Äôs invisible to users, but search engines read it to understand:

* This is a Podcast
* These are Episodes
* This is audio content
* This has duration
* This is a valid media object
* This belongs to this show

Without it, Google just sees a webpage.
With it, Google sees:

> ‚ÄúThis is a podcast with episodes, audio files, duration, and publication dates.‚Äù

That‚Äôs how shows get rich results, audio previews, and proper indexing.

---

# What We‚Äôll Add

We‚Äôll inject structured data like this (automatically generated from your feed):

* `PodcastSeries`
* `PodcastEpisode`
* `AudioObject`

All pulled from your existing XML.

---

# üî• Add This Inside Your `<head>` Section

In your XSL, inside `<head>` (after `<title>`), insert this:

```xml
<script type="application/ld+json">
{
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "PodcastSeries",
  "name": "<xsl:value-of select='rss/channel/title'/>",
  "description": "<xsl:value-of select='rss/channel/description'/>",
  "url": "<xsl:value-of select='rss/channel/link'/>",
  "image": "<xsl:value-of select='rss/channel/image/url'/>",
  "publisher": {
    "@type": "Organization",
    "name": "<xsl:value-of select='rss/channel/title'/>"
  }
}
</script>
```

That defines your show globally.

---

# Now Add Episode-Level Structured Data

Inside your episode loop (`<xsl:for-each select="rss/channel/item">`), just after the episode container opens, add:

```xml
<script type="application/ld+json">
{
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "PodcastEpisode",
  "name": "<xsl:value-of select='title'/>",
  "description": "<xsl:value-of select='description'/>",
  "datePublished": "<xsl:value-of select='pubDate'/>",
  "episodeNumber": "<xsl:value-of select='itunes:episode'/>",
  "partOfSeries": {
    "@type": "PodcastSeries",
    "name": "<xsl:value-of select='/rss/channel/title'/>"
  },
  "associatedMedia": {
    "@type": "AudioObject",
    "contentUrl": "<xsl:value-of select='enclosure/@url'/>",
    "duration": "<xsl:value-of select='itunes:duration'/>"
  }
}
</script>
```

Now each episode becomes machine-readable media content.

---

# Add Real Subscribe Links

Replace your subscribe section with real dynamic URLs:

```xml
<div class="subscribe">
<a>
<xsl:attribute name="href">
https://podcasts.apple.com/search?term=<xsl:value-of select="rss/channel/title"/>
</xsl:attribute>
Apple Podcasts
</a>

<a>
<xsl:attribute name="href">
https://open.spotify.com/search/<xsl:value-of select="rss/channel/title"/>
</xsl:attribute>
Spotify
</a>

<a>
<xsl:attribute name="href">
<xsl:value-of select="rss/channel/link"/>
</xsl:attribute>
RSS
</a>
</div>
```

---

# Add SEO Meta Tags

Also inside `<head>`:

```xml
<meta name="description">
<xsl:attribute name="content">
<xsl:value-of select="rss/channel/description"/>
</xsl:attribute>
</meta>

<meta property="og:title">
<xsl:attribute name="content">
<xsl:value-of select="rss/channel/title"/>
</xsl:attribute>
</meta>

<meta property="og:description">
<xsl:attribute name="content">
<xsl:value-of select="rss/channel/description"/>
</xsl:attribute>
</meta>

<meta property="og:image">
<xsl:attribute name="content">
<xsl:value-of select="rss/channel/image/url"/>
</xsl:attribute>
</meta>
```

Now social previews work properly when shared.

